    "summary": "Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 605–562 BC) was the greatest king of the Neo-Babylonian Empire — a warrior-king and builder who made Babylon the wealthiest and most spectacular city in the ancient world while conducting military campaigns that reshaped the Levant. His conquest of Judah and the [[event:1909|Destruction of Solomon Temple]] in 586 BC, with the subsequent [[event:1908|Babylonian Captivity Judah]] deportation of Jewish elites to Babylon, were among the most consequential events in Jewish religious history — directly shaping the development of Judaism as a religion of scripture and law rather than Temple sacrifice.\n\nAs a builder, Nebuchadnezzar transformed Babylon: he rebuilt the great processional way leading to the Ishtar Gate, constructed or rebuilt the ziggurat Etemenanki, expanded the royal palace complex, and according to tradition built the [[event:1906|Hanging Gardens of Babylon]] for his wife Amytis of Media, who missed the mountains of her homeland. His inscriptions boast of construction in superlatives — every monument was rebuilt in lapis lazuli and gold, every gate gleaming. The Book of Daniel depicts Nebuchadnezzar as the archetype of a prideful pagan king humbled by God — a portrayal that has shaped his image in Western culture far more than the historical record.",
